,"–Male":"Deceased","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","ABT 1140":"about 1140","Abt 1165":"about 1165","Abt 1139":"about 1139","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","ABT 1160":"about 1160","Of,,, England":"England, United Kingdom","Of, Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"BROOKS","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually a variant of   Brook  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>. The optional addition of <i>-s</i>, with no grammatical function, is usually post-medieval, but some examples of the same person's name occurring with and without <i>-(e)s</i> have been noted as early as the 14th century in South Lancashire. The <i>-es</i> in such cases probably has neither a plural nor a genitival function, and the name means ‘dweller at the brook’, not ‘dweller at the brooks’. A plural sense cannot be ruled out elsewhere, but a non-grammatical <i>-(e)s</i> must also be considered a strong possibility.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Brucks  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brucks","meanings":["North German:","probably a habitational name from Brucks (also Brux) which derives from Middle Low German <i>brōk</i> ‘low-lying marsh’.","reportedly also an altered form of Flemish (Dutch) <b>Broex</b>, an old variant of <b>Broeks</b> (see   Brooks  )."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Brookes","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Brooks  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William BROOKS was born about 1140, in England, United Kingdom as the son of Roger BROOKS and Agnes De Covele. He married Mrs William BROOKS about 1160, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1140–":"umbes 1140–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1142–Female":"1142–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","ABT 1140":"umbes 1140","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","Abt 1139":"umbes 1139","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","ABT 1160":"umbes 1160","Of,,, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1140–":"noin 1140–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1142–Female":"1142–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","ABT 1140":"noin 1140","Abt 1165":"noin 1165","Abt 1139":"noin 1139","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","ABT 1160":"noin 1160","Of,,, England":"Englanti, Yh